Steve Gardner writes:
 
>> Current direction?  What current direction?  There is no evidence to
>> suggest that we have a balanced system at present, and what's more I
>> believe the current system to be extremely unfair as the only
>> dependable inputs are Officer salaries.  (Check out this week's
>> Accountor's report to see how fair the distribution of VTs is.)
 
> I also disagree that the current system is extremely unfair. It is
> true that the major inputs are Officer Salaries - but I regard that
> as a fair outcome. Officers invest the most time in the game, and it
> is their activities that allow the game to continue. It is
> appropriate that they be rewarded for this in terms that make sense
> in the context of the game. If any Player is dissatisfied with their
> VT income, they know what they must do: get Elected.

There are fewer Offices than Players.  The only other inputs apart
from Official salaries are Birthday bonuses (once a year), a bonus for
rebelling successfully (a gamble if ever there was one), rewards for
successful proposals and judicial salaries.  Even if we assume that
CFJs come around twice a week, this latter represents a weekly salary
of 2/15 VTs for Players.  A new Player arriving in Agora currently
gets 5 votes and is then stuck.  Say they vote on a reasonable number
of proposals in their first two weeks.  Then what do they do except
give up feeling that they are completely powerless?  (Well, perhaps
they can sell their initial P-Notes, or perhaps use them to make
successful Proposals, a difficult business for a novice, but a
lucrative one; I may be overstating the economic difficulties a novice
faces.)

While I agree that Officers should be rewarded for their contribution
to the game, I do want the sytem to reward other Players.  Would you
vote for the reinstatement of unemployment benefit, or is this also
too unbalancing?
 
> None of this is a direct argument against Plots, of course. In fact,
> I'm not implacably opposed to Plots. But I am opposed to them in the
> current economic environment. If we could find a way reliably to
> increase VT expenditure to, say, 30 VTs/week, I'd be happy to see
> Officer Salaries reduced (by using the levers in LMP to reduce the
> BOS to 0.75 VT) to account for, say, half of that, and let Plots
> take up the slack. But first we need to see if we can increase VT
> expenditure.  I'm going to try to get my suite of 3 experimental
> Proposals distributed next week, although of course much will depend
> on Promotor Crito's choice of Batch Size. Crito?

Under Plots, I would also press for the Chancellor or Cartographor to
be given the ability to determine yield rates for the various
Plot-investments.  This should better allow for the pursuit of a
balanced economy.
 
> If we adopt Plots now, then the only choice for a Chancellor who
> wants to see a balanced economy (and what is your stance on that,
> H. Chancellor?) will be basically to reduce the BOS to zero, assuming
> LMO is adopted. I think that would be extremely unfair to Officers.
 
Sure, I'm in favour of a balanced economy, but I also want to play
with the new ideas inherent in Plots.

I also suggest that our biggest priority at the moment should be to
fix the bugs in the Order rules.  One can currently vacate old TOs
without penalty.  Morendil has exploited the bug already.  Crito would
have fits if I attempted something like vacating all the TOs ever made
by the Bank.  Arbitrary Vacation of Transfer Orders should not be
allowed.

Michael.


