Although it is tempting to count the repeal of R1788 as a step toward
balancing the economy, I cannot but agree with you that the situation
for non-Officers is now unsatisfactory. I insisted that Murphy include
the repeal provision in Plots because I anticipated unemployment benefits
being replaced (more than replaced) by VTs generated by Plots. Of course,
I didn't anticipate Plots being passed in a crippled form. The right way
to go, I think, is probably to reinstate R1788 and let the Chancellor
take this extra income into account when making decisions about the
level of the BOS. Assuming that we do reinstate R1788, and do not adopt
Plots, I'd be pressing for the BOS to be set at about 0.5 VTs.

>Under Plots, I would also press for the Chancellor or Cartographor to
>be given the ability to determine yield rates for the various
>Plot-investments.  This should better allow for the pursuit of a
>balanced economy.
> 

That idea had also occurred to me, and I think it's a good one. Personally,
I think the power should be vested in the Cartographor - spread the power
around, I say, and make as many of the Offices as possible attractive, and
distinctively interesting. But it means more tinkering with Plots before I'd
be prepared to support it.

>Sure, I'm in favour of a balanced economy, but I also want to play
>with the new ideas inherent in Plots.

The idea I find most interesting in Plots is its exploration of the idea
of specialization as a motive for trade. Naturally, in order to achieve
this, it uses rather artificial means to induce Players to specialize.
I suppose this was unavoidable, though. With the rather small number of
Players and limited number of goods we have here in Agora, specialization
seems unlikely to develop naturally. (_Settlers of Catan_ explores
similar territory in a creative way. I recommend it.) 


