Malcolm Ross Kinsella Ryan wrote:
>
>Swann,
>
>I like the Ombudsman proto. I'm keen to see more broadly defined powers 
>like this. It should make for some interesting judgements, among other
>things.
>
>"I Call for Judgement on the following statement: 
>
> The Ombudsman broke rule XXXX, because e did not act in the interests
> of Agora at large when e vote against proposal YYYY".
>
>Could be an interesting case.
>
>One thing I have long felt that Nomic lacks is representative democracy.
>The politics of selecting a representative who is supposed to act in 
>your interests, but is nevertheless free to do so in such a manner as e
>sees fit, is a delightfully complicated issue. 

It is true that representative democracy raises interesting questions
which we haven't really had to deal with here in Agora. But there's a
good reason for that: we don't have nearly enough Players to make a
representative democracy necessary. I don't need a representative in
Agora; looking after my own interests constitutes a fair amount of my
the activity in the game. You can't graft a representative democracy
onto Agora by brute force. It has to arise naturally, if it's going
to arise at all. So I'm not so impressed as you by The Ombudsman. Some
of the toys tacked on at the end might make the position interesting,
but only incidentally to its central motivation, and that motivation
I find lacking in substance.

